# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beach-soccer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:beach-soccer/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:beach-soccer/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 1872 association football match between the national teams of Scotland and England is officially recognised by FIFA as the first international.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It took place on 30 November 1872 at Hamilton Crescent, the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground in Partick, Glasgow.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was watched by 4,000 spectators and finished as a 0–0 draw.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Following public challenges issued in Glasgow and Edinburgh newspapers by The Football Association (FA) secretary Charles Alcock, the first encounter of five matches between teams representing England and Scotland took place in London on 5 March 1870 at The Oval, resulting in a 1–1 draw.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The second match was played on 19 November 1870, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] This was followed by matches on 25 February 1871, England 1–1 Scotland; 18 November 1871, England 2–1 Scotland; and 24 February 1872, England 1–0 Scotland.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Most players selected for the Scottish side in these early "internationals" were from the London area, although players based in Scotland were also invited.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The only player affiliated to a Scottish club was Robert Smith of Queen's Park, Glasgow, who played in the November 1870 match and both of the 1871 games.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Robert Smith and James Smith (both of the Queen's Park club) were listed publicly for the February 1872 game, but neither played in the match.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] After the 1870 matches, there was resentment in Scotland that their team did not contain more players based in Scotland.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Alcock then proceeded to offer another challenge with a Scottish team drawn from Scotland and proposed the north of England as a venue.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] He appeared to be particularly concerned about the number of players in Scottish football teams at the time, adding: "More than eleven we do not care to play as it is with greater numbers it is our opinion the game becomes less scientific and more a trial of charging and brute force ...
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Charles W Alcock, Hon Sec of Football Association and Captain of English Eleven".
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] One reason for the absence of a formal response to Alcock's challenge may have been different football codes being followed in Scotland at the time.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] A written reply to Alcock's letter above states: "Mr Alcock's challenge to meet a Scotch eleven on the borders sounds very well and is doubtless well meant.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] But it may not be generally well known that Mr Alcock is a very leading supporter of what is called the 'association game' ... devotees of the 'association' rules will find no foemen worthy of their steel in Scotland".
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Despite this the FA were hoping to play in Scotland as early as February 1872.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In 1872, Queen's Park, as Scotland's leading club, took up Alcock's challenge, despite there being no Scottish Football Association to sanction it.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] In the FA's minutes of 3 October 1872 it was noted "In order to further the interests of the Association in Scotland, it was decided that during the current season, a team should be sent to Glasgow to play a match v Scotland".
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match was arranged for 30 November (St Andrew's Day), and the West of Scotland Cricket Club's ground at Hamilton Crescent in Partick was selected as the venue.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] All eleven Scottish players were members of the Queen's Park, the leading Scottish club at this time, although three players were also members of other clubs; William Ker of Granville F.C. and the Smith brothers of South Norwood F.C.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland had hoped to obtain the services of Arthur Kinnaird of The Wanderers and Henry Renny-Tailyour of Royal Engineers but both were unavailable.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The teams for this match were gathered together "with some difficulty, each side losing some of their best men almost at the last moment".
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scottish side was selected by goalkeeper and captain Robert Gardner.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English side was selected by Charles Alcock and contained players from nine clubs; Alcock himself was unable to play due to injury.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match, initially scheduled for 2pm, was delayed for 20 minutes.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The 4,000 spectators paid an entry fee of a shilling, the same amount charged at the 1872 FA Cup Final.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English wore caps, while the Scots wore red cowls.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The match itself illustrated the advantage gained by the Queen's Park players "through knowing each others' play" as all came from the same club.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] There is no evidence in the article that the author attended the match, as the reader is clearly pointed to match descriptions in "sporting journals".
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] It is also of note that the 5 March 1872 match between Wanderers and Queen's Park contains no evidence of ball passing.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] At half-time, both teams rotated the goalkeeping duties among their players: England from Robert Barker to William Maynard, and Scotland from Gardner to Robert Smith.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] On a pitch that was heavy due to the continuous rain over the previous three days, the smaller and lighter Scottish side pushed their English counterparts hard.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots had a goal disallowed in the first half after the umpires decided that the ball had cleared the tape that was used to represent the crossbar.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The latter part of the match saw the Scots defence under pressure by the heavier English forwards.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The Scots played two full backs, two half backs and six forwards.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The English played only one full back, one half back and eight forwards.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Since three defenders were required for a ball played to be onside, the English system was virtually a ready-made offside trap.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland came closest to winning the match when, in the closing stages, a Robert Leckie shot landed on top of the tape.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Though the match finished goalless, the quality of play was widely praised.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] "It was allowed to be the best game ever seen in Scotland" wrote the *Aberdeen Journal*.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The reports of the match that were published in the newspapers reveal further details of the 1872 Laws of the Game.
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] Scotland won a defensive corner kick after England's attackers kicked the ball over the goal-line (a feature borrowed from Sheffield Rules but discarded in 1873).
[src:beach-soccer/1872-scotland-v-england-football-match] The throw-in was awarded to the first team to touch the ball down after it went out of play (this too would be changed in 1873); and there was a break for half-time only because no goals had been scored in the first half.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The **2004 Euro Beach Soccer League**, was the seventh edition of the Euro Beach Soccer League (EBSL), originally known as the *European Pro Beach Soccer League*, the premier beach soccer competition contested between European men's national teams, occurring annually since its establishment in 1998.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The league was organised by Beach Soccer Worldwide (BSWW) between July 2 and September 5, 2004, in ten different nations across Europe.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] This season, BSWW introduced a third division, Division C, to the EBSL alongside the already existing Divisions A and B.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Each team continued, as in the previous seasons, to compete in their respective division, including the newly added Division C nations, to try and earn a place in the season-finale event, the Superfinal, in which the league title was then contested directly.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Spain, who entered as defending champions, had looked odds on favourites to reclaim their title after dominating the top Division but suffered a shock loss to the Division C qualifiers and debutants, Ukraine, in the first round of the Superfinal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] This opened the door for France, who had originally narrowly qualified for the season-finale, to ultimately be crowned champions, winning their first and to date only European title.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The league also doubled as the qualification process for the first FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in 2005.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The nations finishing in first, second and third place qualified directly whilst the teams in fourth through seventh place competed in a final play off stage to decide which nation would gain the remaining berth at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] There were eight berths available in this season's Superfinal, expanded from the six spots in previous seasons.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The table summarises in what positions nations needed to finish in their respective divisions in order to qualify to the Superfinal, what round of the Superfinal they would enter finishing in said positions, and the seeding they would receive.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Division A consisted of six rounds of fixtures known as *stages*, with one stage hosted in each of the six countries participating as shown.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Four teams took part in each, with each team taking part in a total of four of the six stages.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] In each stage, the teams played each other once.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The nation who earned the most points at the end of the stage was crowned stage winners.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] At the end of the six stages all results were tallied up in a final league table.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The first stage took place in Marseille, France.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The second stage took place in Scoglitti, Italy.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Spain won their first stage of the season.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The third stage took place in Portimão, Portugal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The hosts earned their second stage crown.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The fourth stage took place in Stavanger, Norway.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] A second stage victory was claimed by Spain.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The penultimate fifth stage took place in Palma de Mallorca, Mallorca, Spain.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The hosts won their third stage title of the season.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The Spanish also earned enough points during this stage to secure first place in the final division standings.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The sixth and final stage was due to be the English stage of Division A, to be held in Brighton (originally to be stage 1 of the division, held at the end of June).
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Sky continued to offer TV coverage, but no new sponsor could be found, and so the stage was ultimately cancelled.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] BSWW subsequently made an attempt to reorganise the stage as stage 6 in Catanzaro, Italy at the end of August, but this ultimately fell through too.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The top four teams qualified to the Superfinal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The final positions of the nations occupying first through fourth respectively determined seedings in the quarter-finals.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Spain were crowned runaway winners of the division, earning the top seed in the Superfinal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] France, finishing in the last qualifying position, claimed the lowest seed on offer in Division A.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Hence the four qualifiers were confirmed at this point.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] If played, the matches of stage 6 would have been dead rubbers.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Like the top tier, Division B consisted of five rounds of fixtures known as *stages*, with one stage hosted in each of the five countries participating as shown.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Four teams took part in each stage, with each nation participating in four of the five stages overall.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] In every round of fixtures the teams played each other once.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] At the end of the five stages all results were tallied up in a final league table.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The first stage took place in Istanbul, Turkey.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Belgium won the first stage of Division B.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The second stage took place in Linz, Austria.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The third stage took place in Palma de Mallorca, Spain, alongside the running of the Division A and C events.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The fourth and next to last stage took place in Interlaken, Switzerland.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The fifth and final stage took place in Brussels, Belgium.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The hosts won the event, their second of the season, and secured the division title after beating Germany on the final day.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The top three teams qualified to the Superfinal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The final positions of the nations occupying first through third respectively determined seedings in the quarter-finals.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The remaining Division B nations exited this season's EBSL.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Switzerland and Austria were the other two successful teams, the latter qualifying ahead of Germany by a slim margin.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The inaugural season of Division C was played as a straight knockout tournament.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] All teams contesting the division started in the quarter-finals, playing one match per round until the final when the winner was crowned.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The losers of the quarter-finals played in consolation matches to determine their final division placements.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The winner of the division qualified into the Superfinal quarter-finals.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The remaining Division C nations exited this season's EBSL.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Ukraine won the Division C tournament title, comfortably beating Hungary in the final.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] Since they withdrew, Slovenia did not receive a placing.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] This is a summary of the teams who qualified for the Superfinal.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] This season the Superfinal was played as a straight knockout tournament.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] All eight teams contesting the title started in the quarter-finals, playing one match per round until the final when the winner of the 2004 Euro Beach Soccer League was crowned.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The losers of the quarter-finals played in consolation matches to determine their final league placements.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] France beat Portugal in the final to win their first Euro Beach Soccer League title.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The success of the three nations finishing in the podium positions meant they earned qualification for the upcoming FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2004-euro-beach-soccer-league] The teams in fourth through seventh place competed in a final play off stage to decide which nation would gain the remaining berth at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The **2005 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup** was the first edition of the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup, an international beach soccer competition contest by men's national teams and organized by FIFA.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Overall, it was the 11th edition of a world cup in beach soccer since its establishment with the first *Beach Soccer World Championships* in 1995.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] It took place in at Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, between 8 and 15 May.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] France defeated Portugal 1–0 in a penalty shootout, following a 3–3 draw after extra-time, to win their first title.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The 12 teams present at the finals in Brazil were split into four groups of three teams.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Each team played the other two teams in its group in a round-robin format, with the top two teams advancing to the quarter-finals.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The quarter-finals, semi-finals and the final itself was played in the form of a knockout tournament.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] European teams gained qualification by finishing in the top three spots of the 2004 Euro Beach Soccer League.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The final spot was contested between the next four best teams in a small knockout tournament a few days before the World Cup began which saw Spain win.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] South American and North American qualification was gained by finishing in the top spots of the 2005 CONCACAF and CONMEBOL Beach Soccer Championship.
[src:beach-soccer/2005-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] This was the first edition of the World Cup in which every continent had a representative.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-concacaf-beach-soccer-championship] The **2006 CONCACAF Beach Soccer Championship**, also known as the **2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers for (CONCACAF)**, was the first beach soccer championship for CONCACAF, held in September 2006, in Puntarenas, Costa Rica.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-concacaf-beach-soccer-championship] The USA won the championship, with Canada finishing second.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-concacaf-beach-soccer-championship] The two moved on to play in the 2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil from 2 November - 12 November.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The **2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup** was the second edition of the FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup, governed by FIFA.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Overall, this was the 12th edition of a world cup in beach soccer since the establishment of the *Beach Soccer World Championships* which ran from 1995–2004 but was not governed by FIFA.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] It took place in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from 2–12 November 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The winners of the tournament were hosts Brazil, who won their first FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup title and their tenth world title overall.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] After the 2005 World Cup, beach soccer continued to grow and spread worldwide at a fast rate.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Therefore, FIFA established the *FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup qualifiers*, to try to allow more nations to play in the World Cup, as well as getting more national teams involved in the sport.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] FIFA also increased the number of participating teams in the World Cup from 12 to a record-high 16 teams.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] This also meant that nations would no longer be invited to play in the World Cup but would have to qualify.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] African nations were allocated 2 berths at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between September 28 and September 30, 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Cameroon and Nigeria were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Cameroon defeated Nigeria in the final to win the title.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Asian nations were allocated 3 berths at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between May 22 and May 26, 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Bahrain and Japan were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Bahrain defeated Japan in the final to win the title.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Iran and China were knocked out in the semi-finals and played each other in the third place play off.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Iran beat China to claim the third berth at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] European nations were allocated 5 berths at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Instead of having a specific tournament for World Cup qualification, qualification was achieved through the *2006 Euro Beach Soccer League* which took place earlier in the year.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The nations who made it to the second stage of the Superfinal qualified to the World Cup being Spain, Portugal, Poland and Italy.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] To decide who would claim the fifth berth, the defeated nations in the competition came back to play in a straight knockout tournament, with the winner progressing to the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The nation which won the tournament was France who beat Switzerland in the final.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] North, Central American and Caribbean nations were allocated 2 berths at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between September 13 and September 17, 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The United States and Canada were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The United States defeated Canada in the final to win the title.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Oceanian nations were allocated 1 berth at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between August 31 and September 3, 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The Solomon Islands and Vanuatu were the two finalists.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The Solomon Islands defeated Vanuatu in the final to win the title and qualify for the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] South American nations were allocated 3 berths at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The championship took place between March 5 and March 12, 2006.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Brazil and Uruguay were the two finalists, meaning they both qualified for the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Brazil defeated Uruguay in the final to win the title.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Argentina and Venezuela were knocked out in the semi-finals and played each other in the third place play off.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Argentina beat Venezuela to claim the third berth at the World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] As with the previous FIFA editions of the World Cup held in Rio, the tournament once again took place at the Copacabana Beach Soccer Arena.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The 16 teams present at the finals in Brazil were split into 4 groups of 4 teams.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] Each team played the other 3 teams in its group in a round-robin format, with the top two teams advancing to the quarter finals.
[src:beach-soccer/2006-fifa-beach-soccer-world-cup] The quarter finals, semi finals and the final itself was played in the form of a knockout tournament.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Association football has long been played informally on beaches.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Beach soccer was introduced in 1992 as an effort to codify rules for the game by the founders of Beach Soccer Worldwide, a company set up to develop the sport and responsible for the majority of its tournaments.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] FIFA has held the Beach Soccer World Cup biennially since 2005.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The first international matches were played in 1993 for men and 2009 for women.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] As of July 2023, there are 193 men's and 64 women's clubs and 101 men's and 23 women's national teams sorted in the Beach Soccer Worldwide Rankings.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Beach soccer or sand football (*futebol de praia* or *futebol de areia*) originated in Brazil, more precisely in Rio de Janeiro in the mid-20th century.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In 1950, the first official tournament was created to unify small neighborhood tournaments that happened since 1940.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] It has grown to be an international game.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The participation of international players such as Eric Cantona, Júnior, Romário and Zico has helped to expand the sport's popularity worldwide.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Beach soccer had been played recreationally for years and in different formats.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In 1992, the laws of the game were envisioned and a pilot event was staged by the founding partners of Beach Soccer Worldwide (BSWW) in Los Angeles, and the sport was adopted by Beach Soccer Los Angeles in 2017, being played all around Los Angeles County.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] By 1993, the first professional beach soccer competition was organized at Miami Beach with teams from the United States, Brazil, Argentina and Italy taking part.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In April 1994, the first event to be covered by network television transmissions was held on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro, and the city hosted the first Beach Soccer World Championship in 1995.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The competition was won by the host nation, making Brazil the first-ever world champions of Beach Soccer.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Commercial interest began to match developments on the field, and growing demand for the sport around the world gave rise to the Pro Beach Soccer Tour in 1996.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The first Pro Beach Soccer Tour included a total of 60 games in two years across South America, Europe, Asia and the United States.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Interest generated by the tour in Europe led to the creation of the European Pro Beach Soccer League in 1998, providing a more solid infrastructure that would increase the professionalism of the spectacle.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] EPBSL, now known as the Euro Beach Soccer League, brought promoters together from across the continent and satisfied the demands of the media, sponsors and fans.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Four years on from its creation, the first step in the building of a legitimate worldwide competition structure for the sport of pro beach soccer had been taken.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Behind the scenes developments were also taking place, with the Beach Soccer Company relocating its headquarters to Europe, firstly to Monaco and then Barcelona, before becoming Pro Beach Soccer, S.L. in April 2000.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The next four years would see this growth consolidated by further progress both on and off the field.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] By 2004, some 17 nations had entered teams, contributing to vastly expanded television coverage of beach soccer and unprecedented demand from promoters in more than seventy countries looking to stage events.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] This growing interest has enabled BSWW to secure sponsorship deals with international companies such as Coca-Cola, McDonald's, and MasterCard, the latter of which increased its involvement in 2004 by becoming the title sponsor of the Euro Beach Soccer League.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] FIFA became the global governing body of the sport in 2005 and organized the first FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The 2006 CONCACAF Beach Soccer Championship served as a qualification tournament for the 2006 FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The CONCACAF tournament saw the United States emerge victorious, defeating Canada in the final.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] It played a key role in the development of beach soccer within the region, showcasing emerging talent and promoting the sport's growth.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] FIFA has recognized Beach Soccer Worldwide as the major entity behind the creation and growth of beach soccer, forming a "highly promising" partnership that was seen "in its full splendour" in the 2005 World Cup, held in Copacabana, Rio de Janeiro.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] France won the first World Cup, and the next year Brazil won it at the same venue.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The World Cup has continued to flourish with the first held outside of Brazil in 2008 and future World Cups spreading as far out as Tahiti in 2013 and Portugal in 2015.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In the late 2010s, significant strides were made in the development of beach soccer in the United States.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The NASSC gained international prominence with the participation of FC Barcelona's beach soccer team, which clinched titles in 2015 and 2017.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] This period also saw increased participation in high-profile events such as the Clearwater Beach Soccer Tournament, part of the Major Beach Soccer National Championship Series sponsored by the United Soccer League, which bolstered the sport's visibility and competitiveness.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In Europe, the Women's Euro Beach Soccer Cup and Women's Euro Winners Cup were first held in 2016, whereas the Women's Euro Beach Soccer League debuted in 2021.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] In addition, the 2019 World Beach Games had a women's beach soccer tournament, and a Women's Intercontinental Beach Soccer Cup was held in 2021.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The North American Sand Soccer Championships introduced women's beach soccer in 2019.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] As of 2026, FIFA and continental confederations do not host major women's world championships, though regional events persist.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The Asian Beach Games, European Games, and South American Beach Games lack women's beach soccer.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Recent developments include the Women's Americas Winners Cup in El Salvador (2025, won by São Pedro for the third consecutive time), Women's Euro Beach Soccer League in Nazaré (2024), and pro divisions in tournaments like Fort Lauderdale Beach (2026).
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Youth and amateur events, such as Beach Soccer Cape Cod (2026 girls) and Beach Soccer Cup Cavallino (2026).
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The rules of beach soccer are based on the Laws of the Game of association football, with some modifications.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] A beach soccer field is a level sandy area smaller than a regular football pitch.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The field is cleared of pebbles and seashells along with any other objects that could injure a player.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The field is rectangular in shape and the touchline is longer than the goal line.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The penalty area is at a distance of 9 metres (9.8 yards) from the goal and is marked by two yellow flags placed outside the field and next to the touchlines.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Two red flags opposite each other are at the centre of the field to represent the halfway line.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The goals are smaller than their standard association football counterparts, being 2.2 metres (7 ft 3 in) from the ground to the bottom of the crossbar and 5.5 metres (18 ft) in width between the inside of each upright.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Each team consists of five players including the goalkeeper.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] An unlimited number of substitutions is allowed, from a selection of seven substitutes in FIFA competitions (the number may vary in unofficial competitions).
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Both throw-ins and kick-ins are allowed, so the pace and flow of the game can be faster than regular football.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Shoes and socks are not permitted; players must play in bare feet.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Goal clearances (the equivalent of goal kicks) are taken by the goalkeepers using their hands to throw or release the ball.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] A goal cannot be scored directly from a goal clearance.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] A game lasts 36 minutes and is split into three 12-minute periods.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Unlike in association football, in professional matches the referee is not the sole arbiter of the end of a period.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] A separate timekeeping official controls the game clock, which is stopped whenever the ball is out of play and typically counts down to zero, as in futsal.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Draws are usually not permitted in beach soccer.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] If the score is level at the end of regular time, the match goes into a three-minute period of extra time, followed, if necessary, by a penalty shoot-out.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] As in association football, each team takes five penalty kicks alternately.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] If the score remains level after five kicks by each team, the shoot-out proceeds to sudden death, with the teams taking one kick each until one team scores and the other does not.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Beach soccer has two on-field referees (the referee and the second referee) who cooperatively officiate the game.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] They may be assisted by a third referee, who acts in a manner similar to football's fourth official, and a timekeeper.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Yellow and red cards are also used in beach soccer.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Unlike in association football, a team can bring on a substitute to replace a dismissed player after two minutes have elapsed.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] However, as in futsal, this period of numerical advantage ends early if the penalised team concedes a goal.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Free kicks are awarded for various fouls.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] All free kicks are direct free kicks and must be taken by the player who was fouled or by their substitute in case of injury, except when awarded for handling the ball, in which case any player from the opposing team may take the kick.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] The laws require all players, apart from the opposing goalkeeper, to clear the area between the kicker and the goal.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Penalties are awarded for fouls committed by the defending team within the penalty area.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] Widely regarded as the greatest beach soccer player of all time, **Madjer** (Portugal, born 1977 as João Victor Saraiva) holds numerous records, including being the first to score 1,000 international beach soccer goals in September 2016 during a qualifier against England.
[src:beach-soccer/beach-soccer] He has scored 88 goals across FIFA Beach Soccer World Cups (most all-time) and won the Golden Ball twice (2005, 2006), the Golden Shoe three times (2005, 2006, 2008), and a record 11 individual awards overall.
